A former commissioner of the National Cohesion and Integration Commission, Alice Nderitu, has been nominated for an award by an international organisation for her work.Global Centre for Pluralism, based in Otawa, Canada, selected Nderitu as a finalist for this year&rsquo;s inaugural award for her role in mediation and conflict prevention throughout Africa.The international education and research organisation was founded by The Aga Khan and the Government of Canada. &ldquo;The need for respect and acceptance across differences is all the more urgent,&rdquo; said John McNee, secretary general of the Global Centre for Pluralism.